Question set 2: For each of the questions below provide at least one graphic as a basis for your answer. 1. How are ratings distributed? Draw a histogram of ratings and describe it. Don’t forget to mention outliers, if there are any. ##Description: The histogram seems to be slighlty left skewed with a few outliers on either side. It looks like most chocolates are rated in the range of 2.5 to 4. Very few were rated 1 or 5.

ggplot(choco, aes(x = Rating)) + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

2, Do ratings depend on the cocoa percentage of a chocolate bar? #Description: There is no clear trend or relation between ratings and Cocoa Percentage.

ggplot(data = choco, aes(x = Rating, y=Cocoa.Pct)) + geom_point()

  1. How do ratings compare across different company locations? Focus on the three locations with the most ratings: top3 <- dplyr::filter(choco, Company.Location %in% c(“U.S.A.”, “France”, “Canada”)) Upload your answers to the repository. Discuss and refine answers as a team.

#description: USA has the most number of highly rated chocolate followed by France and Canada.

top3 <- dplyr::filter(choco, Company.Location %in% c("U.S.A.", "France", "Canada"))
ggplot(top3, aes(x = Rating)) + geom_histogram() + facet_wrap(.~ Company.Location)
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

Leah Question: How does Location effect rating?

#Answer: There doesn’t seem to be a relationship between Company location and rating. Italy does have an outlier of a rating of 5.

ggplot(data = choco, aes(x = Company.Location, y = Rating)) + geom_point() + coord_flip()

Maheeka Question: What is the trend of rating in Germany based on Broad Bean origin? What is the origin of the bean that has highest ratings in Germany? #Hence Beans originating from Venezuala have highest ratings in Germany followed by Madagascar.

Germany <- dplyr::filter(choco, Company.Location %in% c("Germany"))
ggplot(data = Germany, aes(x = Rating)) + facet_wrap(~Broad.Bean.Origin, scale = "free_y") + geom_histogram()
## `stat_bin()` using `bins = 30`. Pick better value with `binwidth`.

#Tess: Does bean origin affect rating?

ggplot(choco, aes(x = Broad.Bean.Origin, y = Rating)) + geom_point(aes(color = Rating)) +coord_flip() + facet_wrap(~Broad.Bean.Origin)

There are multiple origin countries with many beans originating from there. It is easy to see that when there are multiple beans originating from one country, there is a gradient from rating 1 to rating 5. When there is only one dot, we see there wasn’t many beans originating from there. There is not enough data, and it would be interesting to look into this further- looking at origin countries with >5 originating beans, then making a final decision.
